revision.text:
{{DISPLAYTITLE:Complement of HMS ''Bounty''}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}
[[File:William Bligh, 1775.jpg|thumb|{{HMS|Bounty}}'s commander Lieutenant [[William Bligh]], as painted by [[John Webber]] in 1775]]
The '''complement''' of {{HMS|Bounty}}, the [[Royal Navy]] ship on which [[Mutiny on the Bounty|a historic mutiny]] occurred in the south Pacific on 28 April 1789, comprised 46 men on its departure from England in December 1787 and 44 at the time of the mutiny, including her commander Lieutenant [[William Bligh]].<ref name=crewlist/> All but two of those aboard were Royal Navy personnel; the exceptions were two civilian botanists engaged to supervise the [[breadfruit]] plants ''Bounty'' was tasked to take from [[Tahiti]] to the West Indies.{{sfn|McKinney|1999|pp=164–166}} Of the 44 aboard at the time of the mutiny, 19 (including Bligh) were set adrift in the ship's launch, while 25, a mixture of mutineers and detainees, remained on board under [[Fletcher Christian]].<ref name=crewlist/> Bligh led his loyalists {{convert|3500|nmi}} to safety in the open boat, and ultimately back to England.{{sfn|Hough|1972|pp=165–189, 215}} The mutineers divided—most settled on Tahiti, where they were captured by {{HMS|Pandora}} in 1791 and returned to England for trial, while Christian and eight others evaded discovery on [[Pitcairn Island]].{{sfn|Hough|1972|pp=243–246}}

The [[Admiralty]] rated ''Bounty'' as a [[Cutter (boat)#Naval cutter|cutter]], the smallest category of warship—this meant that she was commanded not by a [[Captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] but by a [[Lieutenant (navy)|lieutenant]], with no other [[Officer (armed forces)|commissioned officer]]s aboard, and without the usual detachment of [[Royal Marines]] that ships' commanders could use to enforce their authority.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|pp=49, 71}} Directly beneath Bligh in the [[command hierarchy|chain of command]] were his [[warrant officer]]s, appointed by the [[Navy Board]] and headed by the sailing master [[John Fryer (Royal Navy officer)|John Fryer]].{{sfn|McKinney|1999|pp=164–166}} The other warrant officers were the [[boatswain]], the [[Ship's doctor|surgeon]], the carpenter, and the gunner.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=51}}  Two [[master's mate]]s and two [[midshipmen]] were rated as petty officers; to these  were added several honorary  midshipmen—so-called "[[young gentlemen]]" who aspired to naval careers. They signed on the ship's roster as able seamen, but were quartered with the midshipmen and treated on equal terms with them.{{sfn|Hough|1972|p=74}}

Most on ''Bounty'' were chosen by Bligh, or were recommended to him. However, a draft list of the crew before the voyage includes several who did not sail, including two [[Impressment|pressed men]] who are thought to have deserted.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=54}} Of the eventual crew William Peckover, the gunner, and Joseph Coleman, the armourer, had been with Bligh when he was Captain [[James Cook]]'s sailing master on {{HMS|Resolution|1771|6}} during the explorer's [[Third voyage of James Cook|third voyage]] (1776–80).{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=56}} Several others had sailed under Bligh more recently, including Christian, who had twice voyaged with Bligh to the West Indies on the merchantman ''Britannia''. The two had formed a master-pupil relationship through which Christian had become a highly skilled navigator;{{sfn|Hough|1972|pp=75–76}} Bligh gave him one of the master's mate's berths on ''Bounty'',{{sfn|Hough|1972|pp=75–76}} and in March 1788 promoted him to the rank of Acting Lieutenant, effectively making Christian second-in-command.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|pp=86–87}} Another of the young gentlemen recommended to Bligh was 15-year-old [[Peter Heywood]], a [[Manx people|Manxman]] and a distant relation of Christian's.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|pp=63–65}} His recommendation came from Bligh's father-in-law, who was a Heywood family friend.{{sfn|Hough|1972|p=74}}

The two botanists, or "gardeners", were chosen by [[Joseph Banks|Sir Joseph Banks]], the president of the [[Royal Society]] and the expedition's chief promoter. The chief botanist, [[David Nelson (botanical collector)|David Nelson]], was another veteran of Cook's third voyage and had learned some of the Tahitians' language.{{sfn|Hough|1972|pp=67–68}} Nelson's assistant, William Brown, was a former midshipman who had seen naval action against the French.{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=56}} Banks   also helped to secure the midshipmen's berths for two of his protégés, [[Thomas Hayward (Royal Navy officer)|Thomas Hayward]] and [[John Hallett]].{{sfn|Alexander|2003|p=68}} Overall, ''Bounty'''s crew was relatively youthful, the majority being under 30.{{sfn|McKinney|1999|p=23}} At the time of departure Bligh was 33 years old and Fryer a year older. Among the older crew members were the gunner, William Peckover, who had sailed on all three of Cook's voyages, and Lawrence Lebogue, formerly sailmaker on the ''Britannia''. The youngest aboard were Hallett and Heywood, who were both 15 when they left England.{{sfn|McKinney|1999|pp=17–23, 164–166}}

